RACE.RACE_TEXT: LOUISIANA DOWNS RACE 1 6F Dirt CR: 53. Maiden Claiming Purse 14000. FOR ACCREDITED LA BRED MAIDENS, FILLIES AND MARES THREE YEARS OLD AND UPWARD. Three Year Olds, 120 lbs.; Older, 124 lbs. Claiming Price $12,500, if for $10,000, allowed 2 lbs.

CALLING raced in the four path, stalked the front runner from the outside of the second tier of competitors, maintained that position through out, did not have enough for the win today but ran a game second. MEGANS MILLIONS vied for the lead, settled off of the pace, raced from the middle of the field, remained out in the six path, mildly gained late. GRACEFUL STREET raced from off of the pace, shifted into the four path after the half mile pole, stayed wide through the turn and closed well in the stretch. GAP DADDY was fractious in the gates. PREPAID SPECIAL raced six wide early on, shifted into the four path in the upper stretch, mild bid late. SMILING ANGEL was off a touch slow, raced on the rail, improved into mid pack, and finished even. TENSAS CLEAR raced from mid pack, was in the six path but was no menace.

RACE.RACE_TEXT: LOUISIANA DOWNS RACE 2 1M Turf CR: 81. Claiming Purse 15000. FOR THREE YEAR OLDS AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE NEVER WON THREE RACES. Three Year Olds, 120 lbs.; Older, 124 lbs. Non-winners Of A Race At A Mile Or Over Since June 30 Allowed 2 lbs. Claiming Price $12,500. (If deemed inadvisable by management to run this race over the turf course, it will be run on the main track at 1 Mile and 70 Yards) (Rail at 20 feet).
RACE.FOOTNOTES: CHIEF ALPHA raced from mid pack in the three path, was in between rivals, launched a bid at the half mile pole, gained ground, split rivals at the five sixteenth, cleared the front runner for the lead near the quarter pole, was driven down the stretch un right handed crop, drifted out late into the pat of a closing foe but still crossed the wire first. AFTER A JOCLEY OBJECTION AND STEWWARTS INQUIRYCHIEF ALPHA WAS DETRMINED TO HACE INTERFERRED WITH ANOTHER RIVALS FORWARD PROGRESS AND WAS DISQUALIFIED AND PLACED THIRD. DARE TO FAIL was well off of the pace early, raced in the four path, launched a bid at the half mile pole, improved position, circled the field through the turn, shifted out into the seven path in the upper stretch, was cued and responded beautifully finding his best stride closing down the stretch, was quickly closing in on the leader but ran out of room just missing. DARE TO FAIL WAS PLACED FIIRST AFTER A STEWARTS REVIEW. BOSSHOG THEM DUKES was off of the pace early, raced in the three path, improved position, launched a bid at the half mile marker, smartly saved ground, gained ground through the turn, shifted into the three path near the quarter pole and weaved through horses gaining momentum, closed down the stretch with a full head of steam, was positioned to split rivals and challenge for the lead but had an another rival drift into his path and had to change paths creating a zig zag effect, dropped into the rail to find running room but ran out of time and settled for third. AFTER A JOCKEY CLAIM OF FOUL THERE WAS AN INQUIRY AND BOSSHOG THEM DUKE WAS PLACED SECOND. LI MU BAI (IRE) raced in the middle of the field in the three path, worked in company with another foe, shifted into the four path and passed horsed in the turn, was four wide in the stretch and closing, was with in striking distance then gave way late. ELUSIVE D'ORO raced in the middle of the pack, in the three path, slowly advanced, was asked f or more in the stretch but had no rally. DECLARE WAR was off slow, settled in hands off of the pace, found his stride and gained ground steadily, went widest in the turn andclosed in the stretch in the six path but to no avail. MAJOR DEAL stalked the front runner from the thee path, maintained position then tired after the quarter, briefly had the lead then tired. SHADY GRADY stalked the p[ace from the two path, circled the filed in the four path then mildly closed in the lane. OBVIOUSLY TOO vied for the lead, raced on the rail, set the pace with another rival pressuring on his outside, tired late. NO KA OI stalked the pace setter form the three path, set the fractions in a set then spit the bit late. THERE WAS A JOCKEY OBJECTION. BOSSHOG THEM DUKES CLAIMED FOULD ON CHIEF ALPHA FOR ALLEGED INTERFERENCE IN THE STRETCH. AFTER A STEWARTS REVIEW CHIEF ALPHA WAS DISQUALIFIED AND PLACED THIRD.

RACE.RACE_TEXT: LOUISIANA DOWNS RACE 5 6F Dirt CR: 75. Claiming Purse 13000. FOR THREE YEAR OLDS AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE NEVER WON TWO RACES. Three Year Olds, 120 lbs.; Older, 124 lbs. Claiming Price $12,500, if for $10,000, allowed 2 lbs.
RACE.FOOTNOTES: RUNANDHIDE WIND was off a step slow, raced in the five path, improved into mid pack, launched a bid at the half mile pole, inched out and circled the filed with another contender by his side, shook that foe, hooked the front runner at the quarter pole, hit the stretch matching strides, battled down the lane nose to nose, then finally in the last few strides RUNANDHIDE WIND was able to pull away and score the win. AUX ARCS vied for the lead, set the pace from the rail, raced in between horses, launched a bid at the five sixteenth pole as he clocked an outside challenger, matched strides and hit the stretch in a set, battled down the lane racing stride for stride, in the last few jumps RUNANDHIDE WIND got away leaving AUX ARCS with second place today. HULLINAHURRY stalked the pace setter, settled mid pack, raced in the two path, was under strong left handed urging in the stretch, getting up for third. EAGLEFORD was off a step slow, trailed the field, put in a mild bid late. MISS CHARGE IT showed little. BATES COURT vied for the lead, raced on the rail while he set the early pace, then gave way. MORO FLASHBACK flashed early speed, then faded.
